@Node "Intro" "ListManager.guide/Intro"
@Toc "Main"

Indroduction
************

ListManager is a mailing list tool for the Universal Message System
(UMS).  It does not only ease handling of subscribed mailing lists
(client mode) but also can serve them (server mode).  In both cases
ListManager works as an news-mail gateway, too.

   In @{i}client mode@{ui} ListManager sorts mails from incoming mailing lists
into local newsgroups (import mode) or sends postings in this
newsgroups to the corresponding mailinglist (export mode).

   In @{i}server mode@{ui} - well - ListManager serves mailing lists.  In this
case it sends all messages received to the subscribers of the mailing
list, too.  Messages are forwarded both from the lists mail account and
the newsgroup corresponding to the mailing list.

   Starting with version 2, ListManager supports admins for every list.
Admins will get some messages from ListManager and mails to the special
list-admin alias.  Most people will not need this, or only when they
are away for a longer time.  For details see @{"Admins" Link "Admins"}.

   Most people will use only client mode.  Just skip the parts about
server mode here in the docs :-)


 @{" IMPORTANT NOTE for users of V1.20/2.x. " Link "ImportantV1"}             Some things changed!

Requirements
============

   ListManager Release 3 requires:

   @{b}*@{ub} AmigaOS 2.04 (V37) or higher

   @{b}*@{ub} UMS V11 (V11) or higher

   @{b}*@{ub} ... nothing more


@EndNode

@Node "ImportantV1" "ListManager.guide/ImportantV1"
@Toc "Intro"

IMPORTANT NOTE for users of V1.20/2.x:
======================================

  1. The term @{i}owner@{ui} has been replaced by the more appropriate term
     @{i}admin@{ui}.  As a consequence the configuration variables
     @{b}ListManager.Owner@{ub} and @{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Owners@{ub} have been renamed
     to @{"ListManager.Admin" Link "ListManager.<list>.Admins"} and @{"ListManager.<list>.Admins" Link "ListManager.<list>.Admins"} respectively.
     UpdateLMConfig.rexx will do the renaming for you.

  2. The format of @{"ListManager.Mailinglists" Link "ListManager.Mailinglists"}, @{"ListManager.<list>.Status" Link "ListManager.<list>.Status"},
     @{"ListManager.<list>.Users" Link "ListManager.<list>.Users"} and @{"ListManager.<list>.Admins" Link "ListManager.<list>.Admins"} has changed
     (see below).  Use UpdateLMConfig.rexx for conversion.

  3. Access check matches @{b}name <addr>@{ub} (without quotes).  You have to
     change your @{"ListManager.<list>.Access" Link "ListManager.<list>.Access"} variables manualy.


@EndNode

@Node "HowItWorks" "ListManager.guide/HowItWorks"
@Toc "Main"

How does it work?
*****************

Client Mode
===========

   @{b}*@{ub} All incoming mails are scanned for @{i}ReplyName@{ui} matching
     @{b}Mailinglist '#?'@{ub} (case insensitive).  These mails were put into
     the newsgroup @{b}mailinglist.#?@{ub}, where @{b}#?@{ub} is substituted by the @{b}#?@{ub} of
     the above pattern.  E.g.  @{b}"Mailinglist 'blafasel'"@{ub} goes into
     newgroup @{b}mailinglists.blafasel@{ub}.  The prefix @{b}mailinglist.@{ub} may be
     changed using @{"ListManager.GroupPrefix" Link "ListManager.GroupPrefix"}.

     If a mailinglist does not set a @{i}ReplyName@{ui} like this, you can use
     Klaus Melchior's programm SetFolder in order to correct the
     @{i}ReplyName@{ui}.

   @{b}*@{ub} The mailinglists name and address determined in the first step are
     added to the config variable, if not already present.  The address
     is updated automaticaly from the @{i}ReplyAddr@{ui} field if necessary.

   @{b}*@{ub} For each known mailing list the corresponding newsgroup is scanned
     for new postings.  These are forwarded to the mailinglist by
     sending it to the address found in the config variable.

Server Mode
===========

   @{b}*@{ub} Server mode implies client mode.

   @{b}*@{ub} All mails to the ListManager deamon account are processed as
     control messages.  This includes subscription, help and some more
     commands (see @{"Commands" Link "Commands"}).

     All outgoing mail messages will get the @{b}junk@{ub} flag set, so you will
     not be bothered with them. Further they will be put into a folder
     named after @{"ListManager.Server" Link "ListManager_Server"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} All mailing lists found in the config variable
     @{"ListManager.Mailinglists" Link "ListManager.Mailinglists"} to be served here are processed as
     follows:

        - All mails for the mailing list are forwarded to the
          subscribers.  In this mode @{i}ToName@{ui} is tested instead of
          ReplyName (we are the list :-).

        - If a groupname is defined for this list (see
          @{"ListManager.<list>.Group" Link "ListManager.<list>.Group"}), the messages are also posted into
          the corresponding newsgroup.

        - All new postings in the corresponding newsgroup (if defined)
          are forwarded to the subscribers.

        - A @{"trailer" Link "trailer"} will be appended to each messages, which may be
          freely configured.  If no trailer is specified, nothing will
          be appended.  @{"ListManager.<list>.Trailer" Link "ListManager.<list>.Trailer"}.

     All outgoing mail messages will get the @{b}junk@{ub} flag set and be put
     into the folder @{b}@{i}<list>@{ui}@{ub}.

   @{b}*@{ub} All mails to the list admin alias will be forwarded to the @{"admins" Link "Admins"}.
     They will get the @{b}junk@{ub} flag set and be put into the folder
     @{b}@{i}<list>@{ui}-Admin@{ub}.

Config Locking / Semaphore
==========================

To avoid problems ListManager locks the configuration variable
@{"ListManager.Mailinglists" Link "ListManager.Mailinglists"}.  Thus this variable can not be changed while
ListManager is running.  It's obvious that changing other ListManager
variables while ListManager is running is dangerous!


 @{" Trailer " Link "trailer"} 


@EndNode

@Node "Usage" "ListManager.guide/Usage"
@Toc "Main"

Usage
*****

ListManager can only be started from CLI/Shell, Workbench is not
supported.

   Template: NAME=USER,PASSWORD,SERVER/K,LOOP/K,DEBUGLEVEL/N/K

@{b}NAME=USER@{ub}
@{b}PASSWORD@{ub}
@{b}SERVER@{ub}
     UMS standard command line options (defaults to @{b}lists "" ""@{ub})

@{b}LOOP@{ub}
     Never quit ListManager just run it in a loop.  After one loop is
     completed the supplied command is started.  When this command
     returns an error (return value 10 or higher) looping is aborted.
     ListManager may also be aborted by CTRL-C.

@{b}DEBUGLEVEL@{ub}
     Messages with log level lower or equal this value are not only
     written to the UMS Logfile, but also to StdIO (default: 5).


@EndNode

@Node "Commands" "ListManager.guide/Commands"
@Toc "Main"

Known Server Commands
*********************

These are the commands, ListManager understands:

    @{b}HELP@{ub}
          Send the helpfile as seperate message.

    @{b}ADD List/A,Name/K,Addr/K@{ub}
    @{b}SUBSCRIBE List/A,Name/K,Addr/K@{ub}
          Subscribe somebody to a list.

    @{b}REMOVE List/A,Name/K,Addr/K@{ub}
    @{b}DELETE List/A,Name/K,Addr/K@{ub}
    @{b}DEL List/A,Name/K,Addr/K@{ub}
    @{b}UNSUBSCRIBE List/A,Name/K,Addr/K@{ub}
          Unsubscribe somebody from a list.

    @{b}DESCRIPTION List/A@{ub}
    @{b}DESC List/A@{ub}
    @{b}INFO List/A@{ub}
          Send the list's description file as seperate message.

    @{b}END@{ub}
    @{b}STOP@{ub}
    @{b}QUIT@{ub}
          Stop processing the mail

    @{b}LISTS@{ub}
    @{b}INDEX@{ub}
          List all served Mailinglists.

    @{b}USERS List/A@{ub}
    @{b}WHO List/A@{ub}
          List all users subscribed to a given list.

    @{b}WHICH Name@{ub}
          List all lists, a given user has subscribed.

    @{b}APPROVE Password/A,Command/A,Args/F@{ub}
          Special command for admins to pass the password to commands
          supporting access restrictions (see list below). Please note:
          this command is intentionally not in the user's helpfile.


 @{" Commands supporting access restrictions " Link "ApproveCommands"} 


For detailed information, please refer to the example helpfile.


@EndNode

@Node "ApproveCommands" "ListManager.guide/ApproveCommands"
@Toc "Commands"

Commands supporting access restrictions
=======================================

The following commands support access restrictions via
@{"ListManager.<list>.Password" Link "ListManager.<list>.Password"} or @{"ListManager.<list>.Access" Link "ListManager.<list>.Access"}:

    @{b}Subscribe@{ub} (and synonyms)
    @{b}Unsubscribe@{ub} (and synonyms)
    @{b}Users@{ub}
    ... others to come


@EndNode

@Node "ClientMode" "ListManager.guide/ClientMode"
@Next "ServerMode"
@Toc "Main"

Installation for Client Mode
****************************

For using ListManager in client mode, you need ...

... One User, ...
=================

For using ListManager, it's quite useful to have an extra user who gets
all the mailinglists.  The suggested name is @{b}lists@{ub}.  For security
reasons restrict @{b}Export@{ub}, @{b}WriteAccess@{ub} and @{b}NetAccess@{ub} as far as possible.

   If you are not able to use an extra deamon user you must use the
@{"NoDeamonAccount" Link "ListManager.NoDeamonAccount"} configuration.  The only valid reason for not using an
extra user is that you can only use exactly one email address, e.g.
when using POP mail).  @{"NoDeamonAccount" Link "ListManager.NoDeamonAccount"} invokes a lot of magic.  It's
very tricky.  We propose the use of an extra user for this deamon stuff
handling whenever possible.

   If you are subscribed to a Mailinglist which does not create a
@{i}ReplyName@{ui} in the form of @{b}Mailinglist 'Listname'@{ub} please use Klaus
Melchior's programm @{"SetFolder" Link "SetFolder"} in order to correct this.

Mind the Exporters
------------------

Mind the @{b}ReadAccess@{ub} pattern of all your exporters!  If this is set up
wrong, you will export the mailing list as newsgroup.  This is
especially important for confidental mailinglists.

... One Variable
================

ListManager will automatically add all incoming mailinglists into its
config variable.

   For the case you got some postings to be exported to mailinglists not
already present in the config variable, just add an entry.  The lines
will be parsed one by one using ReadArgs with template @{b}Name,Addr@{ub}.

     ( ListManager.Mailinglists
         "Oberon-A oberon-a@wossname.apana.org.au\n"
         "AMOK amok-l@listserv.uni-stuttgart.de"
     )

If only using client operation further configuration is not nesseccary!

   Optionally you may set a variable:


 @{" ListManager.GroupPrefix " Link "ListManager.GroupPrefix"}  (optional, default: "mailinglist.")
 @{" ListManager.NoDeamonAccount " Link "ListManager.NoDeamonAccount"}  (optional, default: off)


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.GroupPrefix" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.GroupPrefix"
@Toc "ClientMode"

@{b}ListManager.GroupPrefix@{ub}
     This variable defines the prefix listgroups in @{"client mode" Link "Intro"}.  This
     will be postfixed with the @{b}#?@{ub} part of the @{i}ReplyName@{ui}'s matching
     pattern @{b}Mailinglist '#?'@{ub}.

     E.g. if @{b}ListManager.GroupPrefix@{ub} is @{b}local.ml.@{ub} then
     @{b}"Mailinglist 'blafasel'"@{ub} goes into newgroup @{b}local.ml.blafasel@{ub}.

    Again:
          Mind the @{b}ReadAccess@{ub} pattern of your exporters (see
          @{"Installation for Client Mode" Link "ClientMode"}).

     @{i}optional, default: "mailinglist."@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.NoDeamonAccount" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.NoDeamonAccount"
@Toc "ClientMode"

@{b}ListManager.NoDeamonAccount@{ub}
     This is only useful if the ListManager runs on a real-user account.
     Set the contents of this variable to @{b}Y@{ub} (or @{b}y@{ub}) to enable this
     option, anything else to disable.

    @{i}Please note:@{ui}
          This is @{i}not@{ui} suggested usage.  Please use an extra (deamon)
          user whenever possible.

     If it isn't possible for you to use an extra user for mailinglist
     handling (because you are limited to a single mail address e.g. due
     to POP) ListManager uses a userflag instead of @{i}Old@{ui} to determine
     which messages from newsgroups must be exported.  This flag is
     automatically reserved by using the config variable @{b}flags.user@{ub}.
     Please check all other UMS tools which use userflags in order to
     avoid conflicts.  If a tool does not support @{b}flags.user@{ub} please
     notify the author!


@EndNode

@Node "ServerMode" "ListManager.guide/ServerMode"
@Next "PerListConfig"
@Prev "ClientMode"
@Toc "Main"

Installation for Server Mode
****************************

Okay, this is for the guys willing to run a mailinglist.  This may look
a bit complicated but this is just do keep some nerds away ;-)

   First of all you need an alias for your Deamon, suggested names are
@{b}ListServ@{ub} or @{b}request@{ub}.  This may be the deamon user's name, but this is
not suggested since you may use the same deamon account for other
purposes (@{"ListManager.Server" Link "ListManager_Server"}).

   You also have to set the alias @{b}postmaster@{ub} to your own account if you
did not already.  Users of the lists are instructed to send questions
to this alias.

@{i}Please note:@{ui}
     When using @{"NoDeamonAccount" Link "ListManager.NoDeamonAccount"} it's not possible to run ListManager in
     server mode.

   Then you need a bunch of extra config variables for handling the
server stuff:


 @{" ListManager.Server   " Link "ListManager_Server"}                   
 @{" ListManager.HostName " Link "ListManager_HostName"}                     
 @{" ListManager.Admin    " Link "ListManager_Admin"}                      (optional, default: postmaster)
 @{" ListManager.HelpFile " Link "ListManager_HelpFile"}                      (optional but suggested)
 @{" ListManager.Trailer  " Link "ListManager_Trailer"}                      (optional but suggested)
 @{" ListManager.Reject.Address " Link "ListManager.Reject.Address"}                (optional)
 @{" ListManager.Reject.Subject " Link "ListManager.Reject.Subject"}                (optional)


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager_Server" "ListManager.guide/ListManager_Server"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.Server@{ub}
     This is the alias of the pseudo-user which handles all requests.
     All mails with this @{i}ToName@{ui} set are handled as control messages.

     The presence of this varibale is taken as indicator whether to run
     in server mode.

     Enter here the alias you just created.  Suggested names are
     @{b}ListServ@{ub} or @{b}request@{ub}.  It's not suggested to use the deamon user's
     name since you may use the same deamon account for other purposes,
     e.g. BugsManager.

     You may add several aliases, one per line, which will be checked.
     The first alias will be used when sending messages. This is very
     helpfull to get misspelled names, like @{b}ListServer@{ub} instead of
     @{b}ListServ@{ub}. Empty lines are ignored, but the first line @{i}must not@{ui} be
     empty.

     The first alias given will be taken as FromName when ListManager
     sends out messages, like the help-file. This alias is also the name
     of the folder such messages will be put in.

    @{i}Please note:@{ui}
          Do make this feature work as expected, all the names in this
          list should be aliases of the deamon user.


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager_HostName" "ListManager.guide/ListManager_HostName"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.HostName@{ub}
     The name of your host.  In almost all cases this is identical to
     @{b}rfc.domainname@{ub}.


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager_Admin" "ListManager.guide/ListManager_Admin"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.Admin@{ub}
     Alias for the @{i}admin@{ui} of ListManager, this is the person to maintain
     setup, etc., usually the postmaster.  This is used to generate the
     @{b}Errors-To:@{ub}-Header, the footer and several other texts and message
     fields.

     @{i}Optional, default: @{b}postmaster@{ub}.@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager_HelpFile" "ListManager.guide/ListManager_HelpFile"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.HelpFile@{ub}
     Filename (including path) of a file describing the usage of
     ListManger.  Best to take the example helpfile included with the
     distribution.  Change the e-mail addresses at the top and bottom of
     the text to suit your needs.

     @{i}Optional but suggested.@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager_Trailer" "ListManager.guide/ListManager_Trailer"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.Trailer@{ub}
     Format of the informational @{"trailer" Link "trailer"} to be appended to every served
     message.  If no trailer is specified or the trailer is an empty
     string nothing will be be appended.

     @{i}Optional but suggested.@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "trailer" "ListManager.guide/trailer"
@Toc "ListManager_Trailer"

The Info-Trailer
================

To each messages forwarded in server mode an information trailer will
be appended.  If no trailer is specified, nothing will be appended.

   The format of the trailer may be freely configured, the string may
contain some special commands:

@{b}%a@{ub}
     If there are @{"admins" Link "Admins"} defined for this list, the alias @{b}@{i}<list>@{ui}-admin@{ub}
     will be put here, otherwise @{"ListManager.Admin" Link "ListManager_Admin"}.

@{b}%h@{ub}
     Hostname, the contents of @{"ListManager.Hostname" Link "ListManager_HostName"}.

@{b}%n@{ub}
     the list name, e.g. @{b}duerer-klatsch@{ub}

@{b}%v@{ub}
     the server alias

@{b}%c@{ub}
     center this line

@{b}%_@{ub}
     fill this line with undersores

@{i}Please note:@{ui}
   @{b}*@{ub} The width used for @{b}%x@{ub} and @{b}%_@{ub} is the length of the longest line
     plus 2.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}%x@{ub} and @{b}%_@{ub} are not designed to be used together in one line; so
     if you use them this way, you may get unexpected results.

   @{b}*@{ub}     @{b}%x@{ub} and @{b}%_@{ub} are only recognized within the first 32
     trailer-lines.  But you should restrict the trailer to a few lines
     anyway!

The trailer should contain the name of the mailinglist, the address of
the @{"list admins" Link "Admins"} and the address of the server (where to send requests).
The format

     ListManager.Trailer (
       "%_\n"
       "%cMailinglist '%n'  Admin: <%a@%h>\n"
       "%cSend listserv-requests to <%v@%h>"
     )

will lead to a trailer like this:

     ___________________________________________________________
        Mailinglist 'WRITE' Admin: <postmaster@edge.ping.de>
          Send listserv-requests to <Request@edge.ping.de>


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.Reject.Address" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.Reject.Address"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.Reject.Address@{ub}
     Every subscriber's address is checked against this pattern.  If it
     matches, the request will be rejected.  This is thought to exclude
     domains from subscription which caused repeated problems.

    @{i}Please note:@{ui}
          Only the address part will be checked.

     @{i}Optional@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.Reject.Subject" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.Reject.Subject"
@Toc "ServerMode"

@{b}ListManager.Reject.Subject@{ub}
     @{i}NOT YET IMPLEMENTED!@{ui}

     The subject of every message to be forwarded by ListManager is
     checked against this pattern.  If it matches, the message is asumed
     to be a request and will not be forwared to the list.  The sender
     of the message will get a note about this fact.

     @{i}Optional but suggested.@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "PerListConfig" "ListManager.guide/PerListConfig"
@Next "Admins"
@Prev "ServerMode"
@Toc "Main"

Per-list configuration
**********************

Now you have set up the ListServer but there are no mailing lists
specified to be served.  This is what has to be configurated for each
mailinglist.

   First of all you need three more aliases for your (deamon) user.  So
if you are serving @{b}testlist@{ub} the appropriate UMS user must have the
aliases @{b}testlist@{ub}, @{b}Mailinglist 'testlist'@{ub} and @{b}testlist-Admin@{ub}.  The last
one is to reach the admins of the list (see below).


And again, some configuration variables:

 @{" ListManager.Mailinglists " Link "ListManager.Mailinglists"} 

You need extra variables for each of the lists in server mode.  @{i}<list>@{ui}
is to be substituted by the name of the list.

 @{" ListManager.<list>.Alias " Link "ListManager.<list>.Alias"}     (optional, default: none)
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Group " Link "ListManager.<list>.Group"}     (optional, default: none)
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Descfile " Link "ListManager.<list>.Descfile"}  (optional, default: none)
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Status " Link "ListManager.<list>.Status"}    (optional, default: "")
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Password " Link "ListManager.<list>.Password"}  (optional, default: none)
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Access " Link "ListManager.<list>.Access"}    (optional, default: "#?")
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Trailer " Link "ListManager.<list>.Trailer"}   (optional, default: @{"ListManager.Trailer" Link "ListManager_Trailer"})

 @{" ListManager.<list>.Users " Link "ListManager.<list>.Users"} 
 @{" ListManager.<list>.Admins " Link "ListManager.<list>.Admins"}    (optional, default: @{"ListManager.Admin" Link "ListManager_Admin"})


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.Mailinglists" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.Mailinglists"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.Mailinglists@{ub}
     This variable is well known from client operation.  Those lists
     without an address are run in server mode.  Example (only 'My List'
     is served by the local system):

          ( ListManager.Mailinglists
              "Oberon-A oberon-a@wossname.apana.org.au\n"
              "\"My List\"\n"
              "AMOK amok-l@listserv.uni-stuttgart.de" )

     The lines will be parsed one by one using ReadArgs with template
     @{b}Name/A,Addr@{ub}.  Add an appropriate entry the this variable.


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Alias" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Alias"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Alias@{ub}
     If a list is named @{b}Testlist@{ub} ListManager automatically scans for
     mails to the names @{b}Testlist@{ub} and @{b}Mailinglist 'Testlist'@{ub}.  If you
     want ListManager to check an additional alias you can specify it
     here.

     @{i}optional, default: none@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Group" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Group"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Group@{ub}
     Name of the newsgroup corresponsing to the mailinglist.  Suggested
     name is @{b}mailinglist.@{i}@{i}<list>@{ui}@{ui}@{ub}.  If you ommit this variable
     ListManager does not gate the mails to any newsgroup.

     @{i}optional, default: none@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Descfile" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Descfile"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Descfile@{ub}
     Filename (including path) of a file containing a short description
     about this mailinglist.  This text can be requested using the
     command @{b}DESCRIPTION@{ub}.

     @{i}optional, default: none@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Status" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Status"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Status@{ub}
     This allows further configuration for the list.  Just put in here
     the option keywords you want.  Some synonyms have been added to
     avoid confusion :-)

     @{i}optional, default: ""@{ui}

    Private
    MembersOnly
          Only subscribers can write to the list.

         @{i}Please note:@{ui}
               Everybody can subscribe to a private list!  Use
               @{"ListManager.<list>.Password" Link "ListManager.<list>.Password"} or @{"ListManager.<list>.Access" Link "ListManager.<list>.Access"}
               to make the list a 'closed' one.

    Moderated
          (not yet supported)

    Digest
          (not yet supported)


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Password" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Password"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Password@{ub}
     Generally everyone can subscribe to your Mailinglists just by
     sending a control message to Listmanager.  You can restrict the
     use of some @{"commands" Link "ApproveCommands"} setting a @{b}Password@{ub} for the list to be used
     together with the APPROVE command: APPROVE will pass it on to the
     real commands to check it.

     If a password is set for this list, @{"ListManager.<list>.Access" Link "ListManager.<list>.Access"} is
     ignored!

     @{i}optional, default: none@{ui}

    @{i}Please note:@{ui}
          An empty password will not work!


 @{" Commands supporting access restrictions " Link "ApproveCommands"} 


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Access" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Access"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Access@{ub}
     Generally everyone can subscribe to your Mailinglists just by
     sending a control message to Listmanager.  You can restrict the
     use of some @{"commands" Link "ApproveCommands"} to certain users by setting @{b}Access@{ub} to a
     pattern which must match the address of the user sending the
     control message.

     The address is tested using the format @{b}name <addr>@{ub} (without
     quotes).  Matching is done via @{b}UMSMatchPattern()@{ub}, thus you can use
     UMS' multi-line pattern.

     If a @{"password" Link "ListManager.<list>.Password"} is set for this list, the access pattern is ignored!

     @{i}optional, default: "#?"@{ui}


 @{" Commands supporting access restrictions " Link "ApproveCommands"} 


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Trailer" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Trailer"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Trailer@{ub}
     Format of the informational @{"trailer" Link "trailer"} to be appended to every served
     message.  If no trailer is specified nothing will be be appended.

     @{i}optional, default: ListManager.Trailer@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Users" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Users"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

@{b}ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Users@{ub}
     This will hold the names and addresses for the subscribers of the
     list, automatically maintained by ListManger.  Example:

            ( ListManager.Testlist.Users "" )

     The lines will be parsed one by one using ReadArgs() with template
     @{b}Name,Addr@{ub}.  And here's an example with some entries, just in case
     you need it:

     ( ListManager.Testlist.users     "\"Joe User\" joe@site.sub.org\n"
        "\"Otto Normalverbraucher\" lists@verbrauch.in.de\n" )


@EndNode

@Node "Admins" "ListManager.guide/Admins"
@Next "Todo"
@Prev "PerListConfig"
@Toc "Main"

The List Administrators
***********************

For now list admins will only get all the mails send to @{b}@{i}<list>@{ui}-Admin@{ub}.
This alias will be put into the @{"trailer" Link "trailer"} if @{b}%a@{ub} is used there.

   Future versions of ListManager may use admins for automatic reports,
checking access rights and so on.

   If no admins are specified for a list, the alias defined in
@{"ListManager.Admin" Link "ListManager_Admin"} (which defaults to @{b}postmaster@{ub}) is the admin of the
list.  Thus most users of ListManager will not need this feature.  But
you may use this to delegate administration of a certain list to one or
more persons.


@EndNode

@Node "ListManager.<list>.Admins" "ListManager.guide/ListManager.<list>.Admins"
@Toc "PerListConfig"

ListManager.@{i}<list>@{ui}.Admins
     This will hold the names and addresses for the admins of the list.
     Format is the same as for @{"ListManager.<list>.Users" Link "ListManager.<list>.Password"}.

     @{i}optional, default: ListManager.Admin@{ui}


@EndNode

@Node "Todo" "ListManager.guide/Todo"
@Next "Thanks"
@Prev "Admins"
@Toc "Main"

History And Future
******************

Important Changes
=================

This lists only the important changes, since I don't want to bore you
with things like "improofed error-handling" :-)

   @{b}*@{ub} since V3.26
          - fixed: some bugs in case NoDeamonAccount

   @{b}*@{ub} since V3.24
          - fixed: imported mails were not marked as read

   @{b}*@{ub} since V1.20/2.x
          - Trailer may now be configured individually
          - completly re-written in Oberon-2
          - CheckAccess now matches "name <addr>"
          - ListManager.Mailinglists, .<list>.Users and .<list>.Admins are now
            parsed through ReadArgs().  UpdateLMConfig.rexx converts this
            variables.
          - use ReadArgs() for <list>.Status: this enables spelling names and
            more options (on the long run)
          - added synonym for <list>.Status: Private=MembersOnly
          - new config var ListManager.GroupPrefix for changing group prefix
            for client mode
          - ListManager.Server may no hold several aliases, one per line
          - ListManager.MailingLists is now locked and used as a semaphore.
          - may securely be interupted by Ctrl-C
          - Loop will be aborted if loop-command returns ERROR (10) or higher.

Todo -- not all is done yet
===========================

   @{b}*@{ub} priority: high
          - support for requesting FAQ texts
          - support for sending several files when subscribing
          - generate reports following ReportGuide
          - fully integrate Matthias Scheler's MailServ:
                 - reject test for subjects
                 - local address check
                 - ...

   @{b}*@{ub} priority: medium
          - ListManager_Admins.doc
          - complete RFC-Headers, set Fido-Headers for Deamons.
          - Digest, Moderated

   @{b}*@{ub} priority: low
          - better texts
          - complete Admins support (check pgp keys, more commands, etc.)
          - make lists maintainable by admins via mail
          - put all msg into an optional folder (should be easy to implement)
            --> Kai has been asked to send a patch.
          - approve tool


@EndNode

@Node "SetFolder" "ListManager.guide/SetFolder"
@Toc "Main"

Other useful tools
******************

SetFolder
=========

   SetFolder is a mighty tool written by Klaus Melior.  SetFolder
filters mails and sets the folder, as the name suggests.  But further
SetFolder may also set @{i}ReplyTo@{ui} and @{i}ReplyName@{ui}.  Thus it can be used to
make messages recognizable by ListManager.

   Here's an example configuration for SetFolder:

     ( SetFolder.Folder
         "AMOK-L  Comments  \"#?(To|Cc): #?amok-l@#?.uni-stuttgart.de#?\" \"Mailinglist 'AMOK',amok-l@listserv.uni-stuttgart.de\"\n"
         "Envoy-L ReplyAddr \"beta@iam.com\" \"Mailinglist 'Envoy',beta@iam.com\""
     )


@EndNode

